Goals, methods and anticipated outputs of the project
card.desc:
The goal of the project is to evaluate the potential that this new, and soon to be very common, technology can be used to enhance the information exploration experience. 
An agile design science cycle will see continual evaluation as new paradigms of user interaction in a mixed reality environment are evolved.

The output will be the story  the learning’s gathered as this step change in humanities experience of information space jumps into mixed reality. Designing in mixed reality requires finding new user experience patterns and the first elemental pattern being explored will be the timeline. A prototype will be produced which will pose questions for a future design response. The prototype produced will be critiqued in INFOSYS320 -  Information Systems Design.

card.name: Goals, methods and anticipated outputs of the project
Summary
card.desc: Mixed Reality adds another dimension to the information space available in which to project data and explore for knowledge. A person seeking to understand the patterns within data can be physically immersed in the data both alone and with others. This project seeks to combine the analysis of large datasets utilizing the power of cloud based artificial intelligence including machine learning, text analysis and image matching. The techniques being explored will use a variety of publicly available datsets. The project began in 2016 with the development of ChronoPlay which projects data from timelines such as events from the Big Bang until now. This produced a 3D interactive learning experience to enhance awareness of our passage through time. It demonstrates an experiential way to learn and explore any data. With the acquisition of a Microsoft Hololens by the ISOM department the same context relevant datasets are being projected into large spaces such as the Auckland Museum Exhibition halls.

data.text: Added to Shared folder in master branch. Class is called AzureDbContext. Just add it as a component to some GameObject and then use the Get Data Methods. Note: you must pass in Actions (functions with return type of void) to cope with success (and the resulting Json string) or an error. This is because the class is designed to run Asynchronously and so not hold up the UI thread when fetching data. Hence the need for an Action to handle the resulting success or error of the request.

cards.name: Build a 3D holographic mixed reality model of the Universe from the very largest to the very smallest into which data can be poured to illuminate the past, comprehend the present and predict the future
Overarching Topic: Comprehending Big Data using the Exponentially Amplified Information Space of Mixed Reality

cards.desc: Mixed Reality adds another dimension to the information space available in which to project data and explore for knowledge. A person seeking to understand the patterns within data can be physically immersed in the data both alone and with others. This project seeks to combine the analysis of large datasets utilizing the power of cloud based artificial intelligence including machine learning, text analysis and image matching. The techniques being explored will use a variety of publicly available datsets. The project began in 2016 with the development of ChronoPlay which projects data from timelines such as events from the Big Bang until now. This produced a 3D interactive learning experience to enhance awareness of our passage through time. It demonstrates an experiential way to learn and explore any data. With the acquisition of a Microsoft Hololens by the ISOM department the same context relevant datasets are being projected into large spaces such as the Auckland Museum Exhibition halls.

attachments.name: Auckland Museum Exhibition Origins Hall with Timelines

cards.desc:
The goal of the project is to evaluate the potential that this new, and soon to be very common, technology can be used to enhance the information exploration experience. 
An agile design science cycle will see continual evaluation as new paradigms of user interaction in a mixed reality environment are evolved.

The output will be the story  the learning’s gathered as this step change in humanities experience of information space jumps into mixed reality. Designing in mixed reality requires finding new user experience patterns and the first elemental pattern being explored will be the timeline. A prototype will be produced which will pose questions for a future design response. The prototype produced will be critiqued in INFOSYS320 -  Information Systems Design.
